Model evaluation and discussion

From the exploratory plots, the site demand shows a clear daily pattern(low at night, high during day/evening) and a slower level shifts(for example dip around June-July). I wanted a model that captures the overall trend.

  • A smooth trend over time,
  • Strong daily and weekly seasonality,
  • Without heavy tuning or complex deep learning

Prophet is designed exactly for this type of problem. Prophet models the time series as a combination of trend + seasonal components and can quickly fit daily/weekly patterns on half-hourly data(30 min = 1 period). It is also simple to implement and interpret in the limited time available for the assessment, so I chose it as my forecasting model.

Naive Benchmark

As a benchmark I used a daily seasonal naive model, where the forecast for each half-hour is simply the demand at the same time on the previous day(48 periods before). For electricity demand this is a strong baseline, because load profiles are often very similar from one day to the next.

On the last day of available date (2023:09:30):

  • Naive model : MAE = 13.23 , RMSE = 18.64
  • Prophet : MAE = 11.75, RMSE = 13.72

Why prophet outperformed the naive model

The naive forcast exactly copies yesterday's profile, so it works well when today and yesterday look almost similar or identical. However it can't adjust for:

  • Gradual level changes across days,
  • Small shifts in the timing/shape of daily curve

Prophet fits a smooth daily and weekly seasonal pattern and an overall trend using all the historical data, so it can slightly adjust the expected load shape rather than blindly copying the previous day.

Overall, the result suggest that the naive model is a strong baseline due to the repetitive daily pattern however Prophet adds value by capturing the underlying seasonal structure and medium-term changes in demand.

TASK 2

Assume the site has a battery with a maximum export power of 220 kW and an energy capacity of 440 kWh. Assume the battery is perfectly efficient and can be charged to completely full and discharged to completely empty without issue. It starts the day at 2023-10-01 00:00:00 with a state of energy of 220 kWh, i.e. half full. Assume the battery can charge from the grid, and discharge into the site to fully or partially meet demand, but cannot export into the grid to receive export payments.

  1. Produce a plan for battery charging and discharging to minimize cost-to-supply the property over the next 24 hours. Compare the optimized cost-to-supply to the cost the customer would incur without a battery. Visualize the projected state of energy of the battery over the next 24 hours. The algorithm that produces this plan may be as simple or as complex as required.

In[290]:
max_kw = 220
max_kwh = 440
dt_hours = 0.5
max_enery_given_per_period = max_kw * dt_hours
In[291]:
state_kwh = 220 #start with half full
In[292]:
state_kwh_list = []
charge = []
discharge = []
import_grid = []
cost_with_batt = []
In[293]:
low_threshold = plan['price'].quantile(0.3)
upper_threshold = plan['price'].quantile(0.7)
In[294]:
state_kwh_list = [state_kwh]
for i in range(len(plan)):
    demand_kwh = plan.iloc[i]['demand_kw']
    price = plan.iloc[i]['price']

    charge_kwh = 0.0
    discharge_kwh = 0.0

    if price <= low_threshold and state_kwh < max_kwh:
        room_kwh = max_kwh - state_kwh
        charge_kwh = min(max_enery_given_per_period, room_kwh)
    elif price >= upper_threshold and state_kwh > 0:
        max_discharge_possible = min(max_enery_given_per_period, state_kwh, demand_kwh)
        discharge_kwh = max_discharge_possible

    state_kwh = state_kwh + charge_kwh - discharge_kwh
    state_kwh = max(0.0, min(max_kwh, state_kwh))


    grid_import_kwh = demand_kwh + charge_kwh - discharge_kwh
    step_cost = grid_import_kwh * price

    state_kwh_list.append(state_kwh)
    charge.append(charge_kwh)
    discharge.append(discharge_kwh)
    import_grid.append(grid_import_kwh)
    cost_with_batt.append(step_cost)
In[295]:
print(len(plan), len(state_kwh_list))
plan['state_kwh'] = state_kwh_list[1:]
plan['charge_kwh'] = charge
plan['discharge_kwh'] = discharge
plan['grid_import_kwh'] = import_grid
plan['cost_with_batt'] = cost_with_batt

total_cost_with_batt = plan['cost_with_batt'].sum()
print(f"Cost with Battery: ",total_cost_with_batt)
